I cannot generate a 3D model file (such as .obj, .fbx, or .blend) directly. However, I can provide you with the **complete Python code** to generate a 3D house model using the `trimesh` library.

You can run this code to instantly create a `.obj` file of a house on your computer.

### Prerequisites
You will need Python installed. Install the necessary library via terminal:
```bash
pip install trimesh
```

### Python Code to Generate a House Model
Save this code as `generate_house.py` and run it. It will create a file named `house_model.obj`.

```python
import trimesh
import numpy as np

def create_house_model():
    # Define dimensions
    width = 10.0
    depth = 10.0
    height = 6.0
    roof_height = 3.0
    wall_thickness = 0.2

    # 1. Create the Main Body (Box)
    # We create a hollow box by subtracting a smaller box from a larger one
    body_outer = trimesh.creation.box(extents=[width, depth, height])
    body_inner = trimesh.creation.box(extents=[width - wall_thickness*2, depth - wall_thickness*2, height - wall_thickness*2])
    body = body_outer - body_inner

    # 2. Create the Roof (Pyramid)
    # Base of the roof
    roof_base = trimesh.creation.box(extents=[width, depth, 0.1])

    # Apex of the roof
    apex = trimesh.creation.box(extents=[0.1, 0.1, roof_height])
    apex.vertices += np.array([0, 0, roof_height])

    # Create a pyramid by merging the base and apex
    # We use a simple triangulation approach for the roof
    roof_vertices = np.vstack([
        roof_base.vertices,
        apex.vertices
    ])

    # Define faces for the pyramid (4 triangular faces)
    # Indices for the base corners (0,1,2,3) and apex (4)
    # Note: This is a simplified construction. For production, use trimesh.creation.pyramid
    roof = trimesh.creation.pyramid(base=[width, depth], height=roof_height, sections=1)

    # 3. Create Windows (Holes in the walls)
    # We create small boxes and subtract them from the body
    window_size = 1.5
    window_thickness = 0.1

    # Front Window
    win_front = trimesh.creation.box(extents=[window_size, window_size, window_thickness])
    win_front.vertices += np.array([0, 0, height/2 - window_size/2])

    # Side Window
    win_side = trimesh.creation.box(extents=[window_size, window_size, window_thickness])
    win_side.vertices += np.array([width/2 - window_size/2, 0, height/2 - window_size/2])

    # 4. Combine everything
    house = body
    house = house - win_front # Cut out front window
    house = house - win_side  # Cut out side window

    # Add the roof
    house = house + roof

    # 5. Add a Door
    door_height = 2.5
    door_width = 1.0
    door_thickness = 0.1
    door = trimesh.creation.box(extents=[door_width, door_height, door_thickness])
    door.vertices += np.array([0, -door_height/2, height/2 - door_thickness/2])
    house = house - door

    return house

if __name__ == "__main__":
    print("Generating 3D House Model...")
    house_mesh = create_house_model()

    # Export to OBJ format
    house_mesh.export("house_model.obj")
    print("Success! The file 'house_model.obj' has been created.")
```

### How to use the generated file
Once the script runs, you will have a `house_model.obj` file. You can open this in:
1.  **Blender**: File > Import > Wavefront (.obj).
2.  **Unity/Unreal Engine**: Import the .obj file into your scene.
3.  **Web**: Use `Three.js` to load it into a browser.

### Alternative: Three.js (Web)
If you are building a website and want to render a house directly in the browser without Python, you can use this HTML/JavaScript snippet. It creates a procedural house using Three.js primitives.

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>3D House</title>
    <style>
        body { margin: 0; overflow: hidden; }
        canvas { display: block; }
    </style>
</head>
<body>
    <!-- Import Three.js from CDN -->
    <script type="importmap">
        {
            "imports": {
                "three": "https://unpkg.com/three@0.160.0/build/three.module.js"
            }
        }
    </script>
    <script type="module">
        import * as THREE from 'three';

        // 1. Scene Setup
        const scene = new THREE.Scene();
        scene.background = new THREE.Color(0x87CEEB); // Sky blue

        const camera = new THREE.PerspectiveCamera(75, window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight, 0.1, 1000);
        camera.position.set(15, 10, 15);
        camera.lookAt(0, 0, 0);

        const renderer = new THREE.WebGLRenderer();
        renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        document.body.appendChild(renderer.domElement);

        // 2. Lighting
        const ambientLight = new THREE.AmbientLight(0xffffff, 0.6);
        scene.add(ambientLight);
        const dirLight = new THREE.DirectionalLight(0xffffff, 0.8);
        dirLight.position.set(10, 20, 10);
        scene.add(dirLight);

        // 3. Create House
        const houseGroup = new THREE.Group();

        // Materials
        const wallMat = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x8B4513 }); // Brown
        const roofMat = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x800080 }); // Purple
        const glassMat = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0xADD8E6, transparent: true, opacity: 0.6 });

        // Walls
        const wallGeo = new THREE.BoxGeometry(10, 6, 10);
        const wall = new THREE.Mesh(wallGeo, wallMat);
        houseGroup.add(wall);

        // Roof (Pyramid)
        const roofGeo = new THREE.ConeGeometry(10, 4, 4);
        const roof = new THREE.Mesh(roofGeo, roofMat);
        roof.position.y = 7;
        houseGroup.add(roof);

        // Door
        const doorGeo = new THREE.BoxGeometry(2, 4, 0.2);
        const door = new THREE.Mesh(doorGeo, new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({color: 0x333333}));
        door.position.set(0, 1, 5.1);
        houseGroup.add(door);

        // Windows
        const winGeo = new THREE.BoxGeometry(2, 2, 0.1);
        const win1 = new THREE.Mesh(winGeo, glassMat);
        win1.position.set(0, 3, 5.1);
        houseGroup.add(win1);

        const win2 = new THREE.Mesh(winGeo, glassMat);
        win2.position.set(5.1, 3, 0);
        houseGroup.add(win2);

        scene.add(houseGroup);

        // Ground
        const groundGeo = new THREE.PlaneGeometry(100, 100);
        const groundMat = new THREE.MeshStandardMaterial({ color: 0x228B22 });
        const ground = new THREE.Mesh(groundGeo, groundMat);
        ground.rotation.x = -Math.PI / 2;
        scene.add(ground);

        // 4. Animation Loop
        function animate() {
            requestAnimationFrame(animate);
            houseGroup.rotation.y += 0.005; // Slowly rotate house
            renderer.render(scene, camera);
        }
        animate();

        // Handle Resize
        window.addEventListener('resize', () => {
            camera.aspect = window.innerWidth / window.innerHeight;
            camera.updateProjectionMatrix();
            renderer.setSize(window.innerWidth, window.innerHeight);
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
```
